article.description: Seimone Augustus scored 22 points to lead top-ranked LSU past No. 13 Minnesota 75-67 in a matchup Tuesday night of Final Four teams from last season.
article.headline: Augustus, McCarville shine for Final Four vets
article.linkText: Four-midable foes: No. 1 LSU sinks Minnesota
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Top-ranked teams aren't solo shows, and star
Seimone Augustus sure has plenty of help around her with the LSU
Lady Tigers.

Augustus scored 22 points to lead No. 1 LSU past No. 13
Minnesota 75-67 Tuesday night in a matchup of Final Four teams from
last season.

Temeka Johnson had 18 points and a season-high 13 assists, and
Sylvia Fowles added 15 points and 11 rebounds for the Lady Tigers
(9-0), who have now beaten three ranked teams.

"My performance was the same-old, same-old," Augustus said.
"My supporting cast did a great job tonight, as far as stepping up
and making shots when I wasn't making shots."

A junior forward who made all 11 of her shots in a win over
North Texas on Nov. 30, Augustus finished 10-of-19 from the floor.
Her teammates, however, made 12 of 18 field-goal attempts before
halftime en route to a 42-30 lead that hushed the crowd of 7,659.
And this came after a 14-day layoff against a Gophers team that
held its previous nine foes to 36 percent shooting and 53.9 points
per game.

"It's probably the toughest environment we've played in to
date," said LSU coach Pokey Chatman. "We beat a very good
basketball team."

Janel McCarville scored a career-high 31 points to go with 13
rebounds, five steals and four assists for the Gophers (8-2).

"That's got to be put aside," said McCarville, who has a
history of outstanding performances against ranked opponents.
"We've just got to get back to the drawing board and get better as
a team."

Jamie Broback added 18 points for Minnesota, but she was called
for traveling three times while driving to the basket. The Gophers
committed 18 turnovers as their home nonconference winning streak
ended at 23.

"The good thing is we've got three months before hopefully we
meet up with them again in the Final Four," coach Pam Borton said.

Augustus and McCarville made up two-fifths of The Associated
Press preseason All-America team, and each had her share of
highlights.

Cutting across the lane midway through the first half, Augustus
caught a pass from Johnson in the air underneath the basket and
blindly flicked the ball backward off the glass with one hand for a
layup that made it 15-12 LSU.

McCarville, a senior center who spends most of her time on the
high post where she can pivot and shoot, take the ball to the
basket or pass to a teammate on the wing, took control right after
halftime with six of her team's first 10 points.

A spin move in the lane left Fowles on the floor and led to an
easy layup. Then on Minnesota's next possession, McCarville fed
April Calhoun for a no-look, backdoor pass and a shot that cut
LSU's lead to 47-42. But the Gophers couldn't get any closer
against the relentless Lady Tigers.

Johnson, LSU's 5-foot-3 point guard, had eight assists in the
first half. She also used some quick drives to the hoop to make
sure Minnesota didn't focus all its defensive energy on Augustus.

"Our motion offense causes a lot of problems for people,"
Augustus said. "You make the right read, somebody's bound to get
open."

Fowles, a 6-foot-5 freshman who has four double-doubles off the
bench in her last six games, gave McCarville all she could handle.

"She's strong as ever," said Fowles, who had four blocks.

"She can block the yahoo out of the ball," McCarville said.

A 3-pointer by Quianna Chaney gave LSU its biggest lead at 40-24
with 2½ minutes remaining in the first half. Ball control has been
a problem for Minnesota this season, and the Tigers' tenacious
perimeter defense caused frequent problems early. Thirteen of the
Gophers' turnovers came before halftime.

The only other time the Gophers played the nation's No. 1 team
was in last season's NCAA tournament, when they beat Duke 82-75 in
the Mideast Region final. Minnesota lost to Connecticut in the
national semifinals, where LSU also lost to Tennessee.
